content.text:
I really do like that "cluster/anchor hacking" idea a lot, that definitely adds another angle for the player to consider and seems *relatively* easy to include.

Everything else you said feels pretty spot on as well.

Only note in this moment is that I don't love "BLIND" as a core command. Maybe just something like "KILL" as a universal "hard disable" command. Also, I feel like the backdoor thing would be a good place to utilize tags. Like, from cam_01's terminal, you could do ACCESS cam_02 -bypass.

Also, a thought to possibly address potential player frustration: I'm thinking about including an "information pause" mode where you can't interact with anything in-game, maybe can't even see the timeline or puzzle windows, but for the terminal especially you can get a command and syntax list. Sort of let's the player simulate being as skilled as their hacker character early on, and ensures that they never lose because they can't remember a specific command. Then over time they should internalize the language.

To tackle your questions:
1. Matrix search: I have no strong leaning here, but I feel like B vs. C are just different sort of "reflex tests" depending their relative speeds - B is "click this moving object" where C is "click this stationary thing before it vanishes." My personal instinct is that I'd be more frustrated with C than B, assuming that B has the sequence appearing for an overall longer period of time. Especially true if there's a penalty for failure - with C it's a bit harder to identify your window before suddenly the spot you're clicking on isn't the answer any more.

2. Decryption: Here's my current paradigm for decryption:
TOP LINE: the cipher to solve
MIDDLE: input answer
BOTTOM (arranged vertically): animated "keyspace set" for each piece of the cipher

So like:
A B C D
[] [] [] []
A ~ {L, F, R, T}
B ~ {G, I, X}
C ~ {K, H}
D ~ {P, J, Q, I}

Not sure on the exact visuals but I'm picturing like each letter for each "keyspace set" will be cycling rapidly, either changing entirely or swapping around with each other, until eventually the system will eliminate a few possible answers (maybe this triggers the "check-in moment")

So like after ~5 seconds, the keyspace shrinks to:
A ~ {F, R, T}
B ~ {G, X}
C ~ {H}
D ~ {P, Q, I}

Then to:
A ~ {F, T}
B ~ {G}
C ~ {H}
D ~ {P, I}

and so on, based on some semi-random algorithm.

Also, maybe if the player wants to take a guess (or fill in a confirmed element) and guess correctly, it triggers the next cull of wrong answers faster or something.

Anyway, that's just a pitch, happy to hear others, especially ones that skew a little more "realistic" (though ultimately hacker vibes >>> realism)

3. Agreed on Tab autocomplete. Eventually will add the click-to-insert but it's a second-order priority.

4. Minigame failure: Like we touched on earlier, I think this can be almost entirely IC-based. A lot of Signals beyond the very early levels will at least have some sort of basic +heat or lockout-time type IC that can govern consequences.
